{
  "text": " Alright, let's get into it. Number 9, Neutrino, predicted 1930, found 1956. In 1930, the fundamental laws of physics were on the verge of total collapse. Scientists studying beta decay, a process where a radioactive atom emits an electron, noticed something completely impossible. When they measured the energy before and after the decay, the numbers didn't add up. Energy was simply vanishing into the void. For physicists, the conservation of energy is sacred. It is the bedrock of our understanding of reality. To suggest it was wrong was astronomical heresy. Desperate to save the laws of physics, Austrian physicist Wolfgang Pauli proposed what he called a desperate remedy. He wrote a letter to a group of scientists, famously addressing them as dear radioactive ladies and gentlemen, and hypothesized the existence of a ghost particle. This theoretical particle had to have no electrical charge, practically zero mass, and almost zero interaction with normal matter. It would simply carry the missing energy away, completely undetected. Pauli himself was horrified by his own creation, stating, I have done a terrible thing. I have postulated a particle that cannot be detected. He even bet a case of champagne that humanity would never prove its existence. He lost that bet, but it took 26 years. In 1956, during Project Poltergeist, physicists Clyde Cowan and Frederick Rines set up a massive detector next to the Savannah River nuclear reactor. By looking for the infinitesimally rare moment a neutrino actually collided with a proton, they finally proved the ghost was real. But the discovery of the neutrino unveiled a deeply unsettling reality about our place in the cosmos. Because they barely interact with matter, neutrinos treat solid objects as if they don't exist. Right now, as you read this, approximately 100 trillion neutrinos, originating from the thermonuclear furnace of the sun, are passing through your body every single second. They are passing through your eyes, your heart, and your brain. They pass through the entire earth without hitting a single atom. You are completely transparent to the universe. When a massive star goes supernova across the galaxy, it releases a shockwave of neutrinos that washes over our planet hours before the light even reaches us. We live in a silent, invisible storm of phantom particles, a constant reminder that the solid world we perceive is little more than an illusion.",
